<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56195n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56195n">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56195n"> 195(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> green &amp; blue / vitroils <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56195n"><li>FW 603.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n56195n">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n56195n">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56195n">MS BL 47488-80v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:138 <a name="tad5" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tad5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad5.htm#n56195n">Draft: IV&sect;1.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Sulphur also combines with oxygen and hydrogen to form sulphuric acid, a very important chemical compound. This acid is a heavy <mark>oily</mark> liquid, and is commonly called oil of vitriol, and it is made in enormous quantities (many thousand tons every week), and used for a great number of processes&mdash;for making alkali, for soap-making, and dyeing, and calico printing and bleaching, and for the preparation of almost every other acid. Sulphuric acid unites with metals to form sulphates&mdash;thus we have sodium sulphate, or Glauber salts; iron sulphate, or <mark>green vitriol</mark>; copper sulphate, or <mark>blue vitriol</mark>; and many others. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC3"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 87</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Chemistry: Green vitriol (ferrous sulphate: FeSO<sub>4</sub>&middot;H<sub>2</sub>O) is a crystalline solid used in the manufacture of other iron salts. Blue vitriol (copper sulphate: CuSO<sub>4</sub>&middot;5H<sub>2</sub>0) is used chiefly as a fungicide, insecticde, etc.</mm> </dd></dl>
